Formatting Width of String in Python

In Python, you can control width, alignment, and spacing of strings using:

format() method

f-strings

% formatting

ljust(), rjust(), center()

✅ 1️-Using format() Method
🔹 Syntax:
"{:width}".format(value)
🔹 Example:
name = "Ram"
print("{:10}".format(name))
print("{:<10}".format(name))
print("{:>10}".format(name))
print("{:^10}".format(name))
🔹 Output:
Ram       
Ram       
       Ram
   Ram    
📌 Meaning:
Symbol	Meaning
<	Left align
>	Right align
^	Center align
number	Total width
✅ 2- Using f-String (Recommended ✔)
🔹 Syntax:
f"{value:width}"
🔹 Example:
name = "Sita"

print(f"{name:10}")
print(f"{name:<10}")
print(f"{name:>10}")
print(f"{name:^10}")
✅ 3️- Formatting with Table Example (Important for Lab)
name = "Rahul"
age = 21
city = "Delhi"

print("{:<10}{:<10}{:<10}".format("Name","Age","City"))
print("{:<10}{:<10}{:<10}".format(name,age,city))
🔹 Output:
Name      Age       City      
Rahul     21        Delhi     
✅ 4️-Using ljust(), rjust(), center()
name = "Amit"

print(name.ljust(10))
print(name.rjust(10))
print(name.center(10))
✅ 5️⃣ Fixed Width with Fill Character
name = "Ram"

print(f"{name:*<10}")
print(f"{name:*>10}")
print(f"{name:*^10}")
🔹 Output:
Ram*******
*******Ram
***Ram****
✅ 6️⃣ Right Aligned Numeric Table (Very Important 🔥)
marks = 95
print(f"{marks:>10}")

👉 Numbers should be right aligned in reports.

🎯 Summary Table
Method	Example
format()	"{:<10}".format(name)
f-string	f"{name:<10}"
ljust()	name.ljust(10)
rjust()	name.rjust(10)
center()	name.center(10)

